
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `apropos` baraye peyda kardan dastoor-ha (commands) bar asase kalame-haye kelidi (keywords) estefade mishavad. Agar esme yek dastoor ra be doursti nedaaneed, az `apropos` estefade konid ta dastoor-haye mortabet ra peyda konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `apropos [kalame kelidi]` --> 🔍 Peyda kardan dastoor-ha ba kalame kelidi morede nazar.
    🔹 `apropos -b [kalame kelidi]` --> 📚 Justojo-ye exact kalame kelidi (matn-e kamel).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ apropos password

    🔹 List kardan hameye dastoor-haee ke be "password" rabt daarand.

    $ apropos -b editor

    🔹 List kardan dastoor-haee ke tozihaat-eshon exactan "editor" ra daaran.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ apropos printer

    🔹 Agar yadeton nist chejoori chiz-e ra chap (print) konid, `apropos printer` be shoma dastoor-haye mortabet ba printer ra neshon mide, masalan `lpr` ya `lpq`.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `apropos` command searches the manual page descriptions for keyword(s).  It is useful when you don't know the exact name of a command but have an idea of what it does.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `apropos [keyword]` --> 🔍 Find commands related to the specified keyword.
    🔹 `apropos -b [keyword]` --> 📚 Search for an exact keyword match in the manual descriptions.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ apropos password

    🔹 List all commands related to "password".

    $ apropos -b editor

    🔹 List commands whose descriptions contain the exact word "editor".

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ apropos printer

    🔹 If you don't remember how to print something, `apropos printer` will show you commands related to printing, such as `lpr` or `lpq`.
